5557  case NON_PROPERTY: {

5562  lookup_hoisting_mode);

5565  // Split object literals into destructuring.
5566  BuildDestructuringArrayAssignment(pattern_as_array, op,
5567  lookup_hoisting_mode);
5568  } else {

5573  }

5575  }

5578  lhs_data.name());
5579  break;
5580  }

5591  builder()->LoadAccumulatorWithRegister(value);
5592  }
5593  break;

5606  break;
5607  }

2794  // dispatch to the correct continuation point after the statements in the

2796  //
2797  // The try-finally construct can enter the finally-block in three ways:
2798  // 1. By exiting the try-block normally, falling through at the end.
2799  // 2. By exiting the try-block with a function-local control flow transfer
2800  // (i.e. through break/continue/return statements).
2801  // 3. By exiting the try-block with a thrown exception.
2802  //
2803  // The result register semantics depend on how the block was entered:
2804  // - ReturnStatement: It represents the return value being returned.
2805  // - ThrowStatement: It represents the exception being thrown.
2806  // - BreakStatement/ContinueStatement: Undefined and not used.
2807  // - Falling through into finally-block: Undefined and not used.
2808  Register token = register_allocator()->NewRegister();

2815  // when the handler is entered by the stack-unwinding machinery.
2816  // TODO(ignition): Be smarter about register allocation.
2817  Register context = register_allocator()->NewRegister();

2819

2821  // that is intercepting all control commands.

2823  {
2824  ControlScopeForTryFinally scope(this, &try_control_builder, &commands);
2825  // The try-block itself, even though unconditionally executed, can throw
2826  // basically at any point, and so must be treated as conditional from the
2827  // perspective of the hole check elision analysis.
2828  HoleCheckElisionScope elider(this);
2829  try_body_func();
2830  }
2831  try_control_builder.EndTry();
2832 
2833  // Record fall-through and exception cases.
2834  if (!builder()->RemainderOfBlockIsDead()) {
2835  commands.RecordFallThroughPath();
2836  }
2837  try_control_builder.LeaveTry();
2838  try_control_builder.BeginHandler();
2839  commands.RecordHandlerReThrowPath();
2840 
2841  try_control_builder.BeginFinally();
2842 
2843  // Evaluate the finally-block.

1919  // InitialYield;

1789  {
1790  DCHECK_EQ(FunctionKind::kDerivedConstructor, function_kind());
1791 
1792  FunctionLiteral* literal = info()->literal();
1793 
1794  // Per spec, derived constructors can only return undefined or an object;
1795  // other primitives trigger an exception in ConstructStub.
1796  //
1797  // Since the receiver is popped by the callee, derived constructors return
1798  // <this> if the original return value was undefined.
1799  //
1800  // Also per spec, this return value check is done after all user code (e.g.,
1801  // finally blocks) are executed. For example, the following code does not
1802  // throw.
1803  //
1804  // class C extends class {} {
1805  // constructor() {
1806  // try { throw 42; }
1807  // catch(e) { return; }
1808  // finally { super(); }
1809  // }
1810  // }
1811  // new C();
1812  //
1813  // This check is implemented by jumping to the check instead of emitting a
1814  // return bytecode in-place inside derived constructors.
1815  //
1816  // Note that default derived constructors do not need this check as they
1817  // just forward a super call.
1818 
1819  BytecodeLabels check_return_value(zone());
1820  Register result = register_allocator()->NewRegister();
1821  ControlScopeForDerivedConstructor control(this, result, &check_return_value);
1822

1824  HoleCheckElisionScope elider(this);
1825  GenerateBodyStatementsWithoutImplicitFinalReturn();
1826  }
1827

1829  if (!builder()->RemainderOfBlockIsDead()) {
1830  BuildThisVariableLoad();
1831  BuildReturn(literal->return_position());
1832  }
1833  } else {
1834  BytecodeLabels return_this(zone());
1835

1837  builder()->Jump(return_this.New());
1838  }

void v8::internal::interpreter::BytecodeGenerator::RememberHoleCheckInCurrentBlock ( Variable *  variable)
private

Definition at line 4660 of file bytecode-generator.cc.

4660  {
4661  if (!v8_flags.ignition_elide_redundant_tdz_checks) return;
4662 
4663  // The first N-1 variables that need hole checks may be cached in a bitmap to
4664  // elide subsequent hole checks in the same basic block, where N is
4665  // Variable::kHoleCheckBitmapBits.
4666  //
4667  // This numbering is done during bytecode generation instead of scope analysis
4668  // for 2 reasons:
4669  //
4670  // 1. There may be multiple eagerly compiled inner functions during a single
4671  // run of scope analysis, so a global numbering will result in fewer variables
4672  // with cacheable hole checks.
4673  //
4674  // 2. Compiler::CollectSourcePositions reparses functions and checks that the
4675  // recompiled bytecode is identical. Therefore the numbering must be kept
4676  // identical regardless of whether a function is eagerly compiled as part of
4677  // an outer compilation or recompiled during source position collection. The
4678  // simplest way to guarantee identical numbering is to scope it to the
4679  // compilation instead of scope analysis.
4680  variable->RememberHoleCheckInBitmap(hole_check_bitmap_,
4681  vars_in_hole_check_bitmap_);
